results.notes:
Fruiting beneath mature Douglas fir and big leaf maple. Densely granulose top to bottom. Deep maroon/brick red tones.
Gills: notched.
Odor: faintly citrus, slightly metallic.
Taste: same as odor.
Harvested 6 specimens.
Spore printed a single cap directly on a glass slide.
Mounted a single removed gill on a 2nd slide to analyze gill edge features.
Mounted slide#2 in KOH.
Microscopy:
Basidia: both 4 and 2 sterigmate basidia present.
Hyphae: abundant, long slightly thickened toward tips.
Cheilocystidia: absent.
Short pseudocystidia visible/tightly packed.
Ejected spores from gill: Ellipsoid, very small, smooth. Faintly yellow in KOH.
Spore print on slide#1.
Spore print: White.
Analyzed and photographed spore printed slides(also mounted in KOH).
Dehydrating all specimens and bagged for herbarium collection/genetic record.

Comments: Cladonia ramulosa is a wide spread, but a rather rare species. It is very variable and therefore often not easy to be properly addressed. Podetia are usually present and small, up to 3 cm high max. They may be of very different shape: pointed, with very small cups of approximately the same diameter as podetia, but also with wide cups, which are in most cases deformed and have proliferations with irregular, convex apothecia on top. Pale brown color (becomes semi-translucent when wet) of apothecia is characteristic. The species generally grows on acid to neutral substrata, often on heavily rotten tree stumps as in the case shown.

results.notes:
This little mystery was on the side of a mossy decorticate pine log under red and white pines.
I didn’t even see all the water droplets in the field. The second photo is a dorso-lateral view of the dried specimen to show its globose form.
It was globose and measured about 2 mm across.
The only educated guess I’ve gotten (from a mycologist at the U of Minnesota, who saw only a photo) is that it is perhaps the primordium of a scaly-capped stemmed fungus such as Pholiota. As primordia can be very small and very discrete (as to attachment) that seems quite plausible.
On November 8 I found another, a bit bigger, on similar substrate, quite nearby (maybe 10 or 20 feet from first, on another pine log). I plan follow up visits.
On 11/16 I found it very much unchanged. It has been dry and mild, which may explain the durability of the fruiting body and/or its lack of further development?
On 11/29 (now 21 days since discovery) still basically unchanged, despite recent light snow and colder weather.

results.notes:
Found growing in the soft waterlogged decorticate wood low on the side of a large pine log under red and white pines.
My first thought was Badhamia, based on the presence of the long, branched orange strands and my observation 479725 on a larch trunk, but then realized these appear much too large, 4 to 5 mm across, as compared to up to 1 mm across for Badhamia sporangia. And I found no mention of much larger Badhamia species. I still suspect the yellow strands are Badhamia, unfruiting and only coincidentally juxtaposed.
One of the aethalia has been ruptured (perhaps by me) and by the next day is spilling what appears to be considerable white (immature?) spores. On 11/1 examining the dried collection, the aethalia were found to be fairly tough (not collapsing on light forceps handling) and pinkish brown spores were found.
